Airbnb Project¶

This project will use various regression models to predict prices for different airbnb units in Chicago.

This project is partially motivated by my parents prospective trip to Chicago this coming July 4th weekend

The data is a few years old. To try to apply the model to today's market will likely lead to underpredictions.

The goal of the project will be price prediction for the time period of 2017-2020 (this is when the data is from). Perhaps a basic inflation factor can be applied to make these predictions more appropriate for today's prices. This will be done at the very end.

Honor Code and sources¶

All work is my own. The source of the data is from Kaggle and was uploaded by Jin Bonnie: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jinbonnie/chicago-airbnb-open-data

Now to tackle the last_review column. I think this feature should not be dropped. A recent customer review means someone stayed there recently... this could quite likely influence price. A later date means someone stayed there more recently. One hot encoding would certainly not be as appropriate as integer encoding. The latest (most recent) date should recieve 0, maybe we can put them into bins by months.

In [12]:
# this function returns the most recent month/ yr
def find_latest_month(col):
    latest_yr = 0
    latest_mo = 0
    for date in col:
        if type(date) != str:
            continue
        yr = int(date[-2:])
        if yr > latest_yr:
            latest_yr = yr
            mo = int(date[0: date.index('/')])
            if mo > latest_mo:
                latest_mo = mo
    return latest_mo, latest_yr

# makes a dictionary mapping month-year to a bin number (chronologically). We'll assume the last review happened within the last 10 years
def define_bins(col):
    latest_mo, latest_yr = find_latest_month(col)
    print(latest_mo, latest_yr)
    bin_dic = {}
    bin_num = 0
    # iterating through each year and month, making an entry
    for yr in range(latest_yr, latest_yr - 10, -1):
        for mo in range(12, 0, -1):
            # skipping to the most recent year/ mo for the very first bin
            if bin_num == 0:
                mo = latest_mo
            bin_dic[str(mo) + '-' + str(yr)] = bin_num
            bin_num += 1
    return bin_dic

# maps the date to a bin
def assign_bins(bin_dic, row):
        date = row['last_review']
        if type(date) == str:
            mo = date[0: date.index('/')]
            yr = date[-2:]
            return int(bin_dic[mo + '-' + yr])
            
bin_dic = define_bins(airbnb_df['last_review'])
# using a lambda function to iterate and assign bins 
airbnb_df['date_bin'] = airbnb_df.apply(lambda row: assign_bins(bin_dic, row), axis=1)

In [24]:
# fits model, makes predictions and displays results
def train_validate_model(model, X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val):
    model = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    
    r2, rmse = get_metrics(y_train, train_pred)
    print_metrics("Train results", r2, rmse)
    r2, rmse = get_metrics(y_val, val_pred)
    print_metrics("Validation results", r2, rmse)
    return model
In [25]:
 #displays metrics
def print_metrics(description, r2, rmse):
    print("{0}: R2  {1:.4f} RMSE: {2:.4f}".format(description, r2, rmse))
In [26]:
# returns regression metrics
def get_metrics(true, pred):
    r2 = sklearn.metrics.r2_score(true, pred)
    mse = sklearn.metrics.mean_squared_error(true, pred)
    rmse = math.sqrt(mse)
    return r2, rmse

    num_features = X_train.shape[1]
    array = np.arange(len(less_feat))
    plt.barh(y=array, width=list(model.feature_importances_[:len(less_feat)]), align='center')

    plt.title("Feature Importance Graph for Random Forest Model")

For the Random Forest:

In [33]:
def plot_validation_curve(hyperparams, hyperparam_name, r2_train, r2_val):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    plt.plot(hyperparams, r2_train, marker='o', color='green', label = 'train')
    plt.plot(hyperparams, r2_val, color='gold', marker='o', label = 'val')
    plt.title('Validation Curve for ' + hyperparam_name)
    plt.xlabel(hyperparam_name)
    plt.ylabel('r2')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In [34]:
# loops through various max_depths, fitting the model and making various predictions
def prep_for_validation_curve(hyperparams, hyperparam_name):
    r2_train = []
    r2_val = []
    for hyperparam in hyperparams: 
        if hyperparam_name.startswith('n_'):
            model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=hyperparam)
        elif hyperparam_name.startswith('max_depth'):
            model = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=hyperparam) 
        elif hyperparam_name.startswith('min_samples'):
            model = RandomForestRegressor(min_samples_split=hyperparam) 
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
        r2_train.append(sklearn.metrics.r2_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=train_pred))
        val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
        r2_val.append(sklearn.metrics.r2_score(y_true=y_val, y_pred=val_pred))
    plot_validation_curve(hyperparams, hyperparam_name, r2_train, r2_val)

Let's do some grid search and hyperparameter tuning for random forest to see if we can get that r2 up! There are clear issues of overfitting... let's try to keep the model more simple (bigger numbers for min_splits, lower max_depth, fewer estimators). K-fold with k=2 will be used for time constraints (on run time).

In [36]:

    splits = params['param_min_samples_split'][ind]
    est = params['param_n_estimators'][ind]
    max_depth = params['param_max_depth'][ind]
    index = "split: " + str(splits) + ", n_est: " + str(est) + ", depth: " + str(max_depth)
    if index in indexed_scores.index:
        chosen_models.append(RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=est, max_depth=max_depth, min_samples_split=splits))

    print('\n')

Learning Curves¶

Let's plot the learning curve (with no PCA) for more information on how the training and validation is going.

In [44]:
def plot_learning_curve(r2_train, r2_val, model_name, ns):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    plt.plot(ns, r2_train, marker='o', color='green', label = 'train')
    plt.plot(ns, r2_val, marker='o', color='gold', label = 'validation')
    plt.title('Learning Curve for ' + model_name)
    plt.xlabel('Number of data points')
    plt.xticks(ns, rotation=90)
    plt.ylabel('r2')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In [45]:
def get_learning_curve_data(n, r2_train, r2_val, model):
    model.fit(X_train[0:n, :], y_train[0: n])
    train_pred = model.predict(X_train[0:n, :])
    r2_train.append(sklearn.metrics.r2_score(y_true=y_train[0:n], y_pred=train_pred))
    val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    r2_val.append(sklearn.metrics.r2_score(y_true=y_val, y_pred=val_pred))
    return r2_train, r2_val
In [46]:
chosen_models = [RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=est, max_depth=max_depth, min_samples_split=splits)]
best_r2 = 0
best_n = 0
ns = []
for model in chosen_models:
    r2_train = []
    r2_val = []
    for n in range(500, X_train.shape[0], 500):
        ns.append(n)
        r2_train, r2_val = get_learning_curve_data(n, r2_train, r2_val, model)
        if r2_val[-1] > best_r2:
            best_r2 = r2_val[-1]
            best_n = n
    # now using all the data
    r2_train, r2_val = get_learning_curve_data(X_train.shape[0], r2_train, r2_val, model)
    if r2_val[-1] > best_r2:
            best_r2 = r2_val[-1]
            best_n = X_train.shape[0]
    model_name = str(model)
    ns.append(X_train.shape[0])
    plot_learning_curve(r2_train, r2_val, model_name, ns)
    print("Peak validation results occurred when {} data points were used!".format(best_n))

# fits model, makes predictions and displays results
def train_test_model(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    model = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    train_r2, train_rmse, train_mae, train_mape = get_metrics2(y_train, train_pred)
    print_metrics2("Train results", train_r2, train_rmse, train_mae, train_mape)
    test_r2, test_rmse, test_mae, test_mape = get_metrics2(y_test, test_pred)
    print_metrics2("Test results", test_r2, test_rmse, test_mae, test_mape)
    
    return model, [train_r2, test_r2], [train_rmse, test_rmse], [train_mae, test_mae], [train_mape, test_mape]

#displays metrics (rather than use the function way above in the code I will just add a 2 to the end)
def print_metrics2(description, r2, rmse, mae, mape):
    print("{0}: R2  {1:.4f} RMSE: {2:.4f} MAE: {3: .4f} MAPE: {4: .4f}".format(description, r2, rmse, mae, mape))
    
# returns regression metrics (rather than use the function way above in the code I will just add a 2 to the end)
def get_metrics2(true, pred):
    r2 = sklearn.metrics.r2_score(true, pred)
    mse = sklearn.metrics.mean_squared_error(true, pred)
    rmse = math.sqrt(mse)
    mae = sklearn.metrics.mean_absolute_error(true, pred)
    mape = sklearn.metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(true, pred)
    return r2, rmse, mae, mape

Wow that's low!

We know the data was taken from a few years ago (the latest reviews were done in late 2020) - we will assume it is an average of 3-4 years old (2019). Using this source https://ipropertymanagement.com/research/average-rent-increase-per-year from 2019 to 2020 rent increased on average (we'll assume airbnb prices in Chicago match this) by 3%, from 2020 to 2021 2%, from 2021 to 2022 2% and finally we'll assume another 1% by mid July this year

In [60]:
increases = [1.03, 1.02, 1.02, 1.01]
for increase in increases:
    old_pred *= increase
final_pred = old_pred
print(round(final_pred, 2))

134.08

This looks very low!! Especially for holidays! Perhaps the model is quite low and also the price increases in airbnb are much greater than the renting... especially for July 4th weekend (they've told me they are finding prices in the high $200's at the low end)

One thing that this data does not capture is time. An airbnb around July 4th will be substantially higher than in the frigid Chicago winters. Having some sort of time feature would be benficial for a more thorough analysis.

If I had more time I would do further analysis of the MLP model and also try to get additional time-based data and more recent data. I would look at feature crosses and potentially removing some features.

Overall although my prediction is certainly lower than market data, I think the project was succesful in modeling the data. I learned a lot by completing this project and thoroughly enjoyed it!
